  {# ── How It Works ───────────────────────────────────── #}
  <section>
    <h2 class="text-[11px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-muted mb-3">How It Works</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <p>
        After each session, KJ jots down the sets and tunes as best he can remember. Slime then enriches that data — looking up each tune on <a href="https://thesession.org" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-accent hover:underline font-medium">TheSession.org</a>, finding the right settings (specific transcriptions), and linking everything together.
      </p>
      <p>
        The result is a structured record where every tune links to its sheet music and every set links back to its source. The whole thing is <a href="https://github.com/kocopelly/nashville-folk-session" target="_blank" rel="noopener" class="text-accent hover:underline font-medium">open source</a>.
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

  {# ── Divider ────────────────────────────────────────── #}
  <hr class="border-border">

  {# ── Submit a Session ─────────────────────────────────── #}
  <section>
    <h2 class="text-[11px] font-bold uppercase tracking-[0.2em] text-muted mb-3">Submit a Session</h2>
    <div class="space-y-4">
      <p>
        Want to get your session's tunes on this site? Email Slime at <a href="mailto:slimethebot@proton.me" class="text-accent hover:underline font-medium">slimethebot@proton.me</a> with what you played. No special format needed — just tell us:
      </p>
      <ul class="list-disc pl-5 space-y-1">
        <li>The <strong>date</strong> and <strong>venue</strong> (or session name)</li>
        <li>The <strong>tunes</strong> — names are enough, even approximate ones</li>
        <li><strong>Keys</strong> if you know them (if not, we'll figure it out)</li>
        <li>Which tunes were played <strong>together as sets</strong>, if you remember</li>
      </ul>
      <p>
        Slime will look everything up on TheSession, match the tunes, find the sheet music, and put together a draft. You'll get a preview link to check before anything goes live — if a key is wrong or a tune got misidentified, just reply and we'll fix it.
      </p>
      <p>
        You can also email to <strong>report a correction</strong> on something already on the site, or to <strong>add a new session series</strong> (a recurring session at a venue we don't track yet).
      </p>
    </div>
  </section>

